# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: light-probes
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:light-probes/cube-map] The same cube mapping as above rendered as a 3D view.
[src:light-probes/cube-map] In computer graphics, **cube mapping** is a method of environment mapping that uses the six faces of a cube as the map shape.
[src:light-probes/cube-map] The environment is projected onto the sides of a cube and stored as six square textures, or unfolded into six regions of a single texture.
[src:light-probes/cube-map] The cube map is generated by first rendering the scene six times from a viewpoint, with the views defined by a 90 degree view frustum representing each cube face.
[src:light-probes/cube-map] Or if the environment is first considered to be projected onto a sphere, then each face of the cube is its gnomonic projection.
[src:light-probes/cube-map] In the majority of cases, cube mapping is preferred over the older method of sphere mapping because it eliminates many of the problems that are inherent in sphere mapping such as image distortion, viewpoint dependency, and computational inefficiency.
[src:light-probes/cube-map] Also, cube mapping provides a much larger capacity to support real-time rendering of reflections relative to sphere mapping because the combination of inefficiency and viewpoint dependency severely limits the ability of sphere mapping to be applied when there is a consistently changing viewpoint.
[src:light-probes/cube-map] Variants of cube mapping are also commonly used in 360 video projection.
[src:light-probes/cube-map] Cube mapping was first proposed in 1986 by Ned Greene in his paper "Environment Mapping and Other Applications of World Projections", ten years after environment mapping was first put forward by Jim Blinn and Martin Newell.
[src:light-probes/cube-map] However, hardware limitations on the ability to access six texture images simultaneously made it infeasible to implement cube mapping without further technological developments.
[src:light-probes/cube-map] This problem was remedied in 1999 with the release of the Nvidia GeForce 256.
[src:light-probes/cube-map] Nvidia touted cube mapping in hardware as "a breakthrough image quality feature of GeForce 256 that ... will allow developers to create accurate, real-time reflections.
[src:light-probes/cube-map] Cube mapping is preferred over other methods of environment mapping because of its relative simplicity.
[src:light-probes/cube-map] Cube mapping also produces results that are similar to those obtained by ray tracing, but is much more computationally efficient – the moderate reduction in quality is compensated for by large gains in efficiency.
[src:light-probes/cube-map] Pre-dating cube mapping, sphere mapping has many inherent flaws that made it impractical for most applications.
[src:light-probes/cube-map] Sphere mapping is view-dependent, meaning that a different texture is necessary for each viewpoint.
[src:light-probes/cube-map] Therefore, in applications where the viewpoint is mobile, it would be necessary to dynamically generate a new sphere mapping for each new viewpoint (or, to pre-generate a mapping for every viewpoint).
[src:light-probes/cube-map] Also, a texture mapped onto a sphere's surface must be stretched and compressed, and warping and distortion (particularly along the edge of the sphere) are a direct consequence of this.
[src:light-probes/cube-map] Although these image flaws can be reduced using certain tricks and techniques like "pre-stretching", this just adds another layer of complexity to sphere mapping.
[src:light-probes/cube-map] Paraboloid mapping provides some improvement on the limitations of sphere mapping, however it requires two rendering passes in addition to special image warping operations and more involved computation.
[src:light-probes/cube-map] Conversely, cube mapping requires only a single render pass, and due to its simple nature, is very easy for developers to comprehend and generate.
[src:light-probes/cube-map] Also, cube mapping uses the entire resolution of the texture image, compared to sphere and paraboloid mappings, which also allows it to use lower resolution images to achieve the same quality.
[src:light-probes/cube-map] Although handling the seams of the cube map is a problem, algorithms have been developed to handle seam behavior and result in a seamless reflection.
[src:light-probes/cube-map] Disadvantages include discontinuity, a high about of indexing, linear interpolation of vectors (when calculated in hardware), filtering across texture map boundaries, and possibly the need for multiple textures.
[src:light-probes/cube-map] Computer-aided design (CAD) programs use specular highlights as visual cues to convey a sense of surface curvature when rendering 3D objects.
[src:light-probes/cube-map] However, many CAD programs exhibit problems in sampling specular highlights because the specular lighting computations are only performed at the vertices of the mesh used to represent the object, and interpolation is used to estimate lighting across the surface of the object.
[src:light-probes/cube-map] Problems occur when the mesh vertices are not dense enough, resulting in insufficient sampling of the specular lighting.
[src:light-probes/cube-map] This in turn results in highlights with brightness proportionate to the distance from mesh vertices, ultimately compromising the visual cues that indicate curvature.
[src:light-probes/cube-map] However, this problem cannot be solved by simply creating a denser mesh, as this can greatly reduce the efficiency of object rendering.
[src:light-probes/cube-map] Cube maps provide a fairly straightforward and efficient solution to rendering stable specular highlights.
[src:light-probes/cube-map] Multiple specular highlights can be encoded into a cube map texture, which can then be accessed by interpolating across the surface's reflection vector to supply coordinates.
[src:light-probes/cube-map] Relative to computing lighting at individual vertices, this method provides cleaner results that more accurately represent curvature.
[src:light-probes/cube-map] Another advantage to this method is that it scales well, as additional specular highlights can be encoded into the texture at no increase in the cost of rendering.
[src:light-probes/cube-map] However, this approach is limited in that the light sources must be either distant or infinite lights, although this is usually the case in CAD programs.
[src:light-probes/cube-map] Renders using cubemaps can look better in outdoor scenes.
[src:light-probes/cube-map] Perhaps the most advanced application of cube mapping is to create pre-rendered panoramic sky images which are then rendered by the graphical engine as faces of a cube at practically infinite distance with the view point located in the center of the cube.
[src:light-probes/cube-map] The perspective projection of the cube faces done by the graphics engine undoes the effects of projecting the environment to create the cube map, so that the observer experiences an illusion of being surrounded by the scene which was used to generate the skybox.
[src:light-probes/cube-map] This technique has found a widespread use in video games since it allows designers to add complex (albeit not explorable) environments to a game at almost no performance cost.
[src:light-probes/cube-map] Cube maps can be useful for modelling outdoor illumination accurately.
[src:light-probes/cube-map] Simply modelling sunlight as a single infinite light oversimplifies outdoor illumination and results in unrealistic lighting.
[src:light-probes/cube-map] Although plenty of light does come from the sun, the scattering of rays in the atmosphere causes the whole sky to act as a light source (often referred to as skylight illumination).
[src:light-probes/cube-map] However, by using a cube map, the diffuse contribution from skylight illumination can be captured.
[src:light-probes/cube-map] Unlike environment maps where the reflection vector is used, this method accesses the cube map based on the surface normal vector to provide a fast approximation of the diffuse illumination from the skylight.
[src:light-probes/cube-map] The one downside to this method is that computing cube maps to properly represent a skylight is very complex; one recent process is computing the spherical harmonic basis that best represents the low frequency diffuse illumination from the cube map.
[src:light-probes/cube-map] However, a considerable amount of research has been done to effectively model skylight illumination.
[src:light-probes/cube-map] Basic environment mapping uses a static cube map – although the object can be moved and distorted, the reflected environment stays consistent.
[src:light-probes/cube-map] However, a cube map texture can be consistently updated to represent a dynamically changing environment (for example, trees swaying in the wind).
[src:light-probes/cube-map] A simple yet costly way to generate dynamic reflections involves building the cube maps at runtime for every frame.
[src:light-probes/cube-map] Although this is far less efficient than static mapping because of additional rendering steps, it can still be performed at interactive rates.
[src:light-probes/cube-map] However, this technique does not scale well when multiple reflective objects are present.
[src:light-probes/cube-map] A unique dynamic environment map is usually required for each reflective object.
[src:light-probes/cube-map] Also, further complications are added if reflective objects can reflect each other – dynamic cube maps can be recursively generated, approximating the effects normally generated using raytracing.
[src:light-probes/cube-map] An algorithm for global illumination computation at interactive rates using a cube map data structure, was presented at ICCVG 2002.
[src:light-probes/cube-map] Another application which found widespread use in video games is projective texture mapping.
[src:light-probes/cube-map] It relies on cube maps to project images of an environment onto the surrounding scene; for example, a point light source is tied to a cube map which is a panoramic image shot from inside a lantern cage or a window frame through which the light is filtering.
[src:light-probes/cube-map] This enables a game developer to achieve realistic lighting without having to complicate the scene geometry or resort to expensive real-time shadow volume computations.
[src:light-probes/cube-map] A cube texture indexes six texture maps from 0 to 5 in order: positive X, negative X, positive Y, negative Y, positive Z, negative Z.
[src:light-probes/cube-map] The images are stored with the origin at the lower left of the image.
[src:light-probes/cube-map] The positive X and Y faces must reverse the Z coordinate and the negative Z face must negate the X coordinate.
[src:light-probes/environment-mapping] In computer graphics, **reflection mapping** or **environment mapping** is an efficient image-based lighting technique for approximating the appearance of a reflective surface by means of a precomputed texture.
[src:light-probes/environment-mapping] The texture is used to store the image of the distant environment surrounding the rendered object.
[src:light-probes/environment-mapping] Several ways of storing the surrounding environment have been employed.
[src:light-probes/environment-mapping] The first technique was sphere mapping, in which a single texture contains the image of the surroundings as reflected on a spherical mirror.
[src:light-probes/environment-mapping] It has been almost entirely surpassed by cube mapping, in which the environment is projected onto the six faces of a cube and stored as six square textures or unfolded into six square regions of a single texture.
[src:light-probes/environment-mapping] Other projections that have some superior mathematical or computational properties include the paraboloid mapping, the pyramid mapping, the octahedron mapping, and the HEALPix mapping.
[src:light-probes/environment-mapping] Reflection mapping is one of several approaches to reflection rendering, alongside e.g. screen space reflections or ray tracing which computes the exact reflection by tracing a ray of light and following its optical path.
[src:light-probes/environment-mapping] The reflection color used in the shading computation at a pixel is determined by calculating the reflection vector at the point on the object and mapping it to the texel in the environment map.
[src:light-probes/environment-mapping] However, in most circumstances a mapped reflection is only an approximation of the real reflection.
[src:light-probes/environment-mapping] The object being shaded is convex, such that it contains no self-interreflections.
[src:light-probes/environment-mapping] When this is not the case the object does not appear in the reflection; only the environment does.
[src:light-probes/environment-mapping] Environment mapping is generally the fastest method of rendering a reflective surface.
[src:light-probes/environment-mapping] To further increase the speed of rendering, the renderer may calculate the position of the reflected ray at each vertex.
[src:light-probes/environment-mapping] Then, the position is interpolated across polygons to which the vertex is attached.
[src:light-probes/environment-mapping] This eliminates the need for recalculating every pixel's reflection direction.
[src:light-probes/environment-mapping] If normal mapping is used, each polygon has many face normals (the direction a given point on a polygon is facing), which can be used in tandem with an environment map to produce a more realistic reflection.
[src:light-probes/environment-mapping] In this case, the angle of reflection at a given point on a polygon will take the normal map into consideration.
[src:light-probes/environment-mapping] This technique is used to make an otherwise flat surface appear textured, for example corrugated metal, or brushed aluminium.
[src:light-probes/environment-mapping] Sphere mapping represents the sphere of incident illumination as though it were seen in the reflection of a reflective sphere through an orthographic camera.
[src:light-probes/environment-mapping] The texture image can be created by approximating this ideal setup, or using a fisheye lens or via prerendering a scene with a spherical mapping.
[src:light-probes/environment-mapping] The spherical mapping suffers from limitations that detract from the realism of resulting renderings.
[src:light-probes/environment-mapping] The spherical mapping also wastes pixels that are in the square but not in the sphere.
[src:light-probes/environment-mapping] The artifacts of the spherical mapping are so severe that it is effective only for viewpoints near that of the virtual orthographic camera.
[src:light-probes/environment-mapping] Cube mapping and other polyhedron mappings address the severe distortion of sphere maps.
[src:light-probes/environment-mapping] If cube maps are made and filtered correctly, they have no visible seams, and can be used independent of the viewpoint of the often-virtual camera acquiring the map.
[src:light-probes/environment-mapping] Cube and other polyhedron maps have since superseded sphere maps in most computer graphics applications, with the exception of acquiring image-based lighting.
[src:light-probes/environment-mapping] Image-based lighting can be done with parallax-corrected cube maps.
[src:light-probes/environment-mapping] Generally, cube mapping uses the same skybox that is used in outdoor renderings.
[src:light-probes/environment-mapping] Cube-mapped reflection is done by determining the vector that the object is being viewed at.
[src:light-probes/environment-mapping] This *camera ray* is reflected about the surface normal of where the camera vector intersects the object.
[src:light-probes/environment-mapping] This results in the *reflected ray* which is then passed to the cube map to get the texel which provides the radiance value used in the lighting calculation.
[src:light-probes/environment-mapping] This creates the effect that the object is reflective.
[src:light-probes/environment-mapping] HEALPix environment mapping is similar to the other polyhedron mappings, but can be hierarchical, thus providing a unified framework for generating polyhedra that better approximate the sphere.
[src:light-probes/environment-mapping] This allows lower distortion at the cost of increased computation.
[src:light-probes/environment-mapping] In 1974, Edwin Catmull created an algorithm for "rendering images of bivariate surface patches" which worked directly with their mathematical definition.
[src:light-probes/environment-mapping] Gene Miller experimented with spherical environment mapping in 1982 at MAGI.
[src:light-probes/environment-mapping] Wolfgang Heidrich introduced Paraboloid Mapping in 1998.
[src:light-probes/environment-mapping] Emil Praun introduced Octahedron Mapping in 2003.
[src:light-probes/environment-mapping] Mauro Steigleder introduced Pyramid Mapping in 2005.
[src:light-probes/environment-mapping] Tien-Tsin Wong, et al. introduced the existing HEALPix mapping for rendering in 2006.
[src:light-probes/irradiance] In radiometry, **irradiance** is the radiant flux *received* by a *surface* per unit area.
[src:light-probes/irradiance] The SI unit of irradiance is the watt per square metre (symbol W⋅m−2 or W/m2).
[src:light-probes/irradiance] The CGS unit erg per square centimetre per second (erg⋅cm−2⋅s−1) is often used in astronomy.
[src:light-probes/irradiance] Irradiance is often called intensity, but this term is avoided in radiometry where such usage leads to confusion with radiant intensity.
[src:light-probes/irradiance] In astrophysics, irradiance is called *radiant flux*.
[src:light-probes/irradiance] The radiant flux *emitted* by a surface is called radiant exitance.
[src:light-probes/irradiance] For a propagating *sinusoidal* linearly polarized electromagnetic plane wave, the Poynting vector always points to the direction of propagation while oscillating in magnitude.
[src:light-probes/irradiance] This formula assumes that the magnetic susceptibility is negligible; i.e. that *μ*r ≈ 1 (*μ* ≈ μ0) where *μ*r is the relative magnetic permeability of the propagation medium.
[src:light-probes/irradiance] This assumption is typically valid in transparent media in the optical frequency range.
[src:light-probes/irradiance] A point source of light produces spherical wavefronts.
[src:light-probes/irradiance] The irradiance in this case varies inversely with the square of the distance from the source.
[src:light-probes/irradiance] For quick approximations, this equation indicates that doubling the distance reduces irradiation to one quarter; or similarly, to double irradiation, reduce the distance to 71%.
[src:light-probes/irradiance] In astronomy, stars are routinely treated as point sources even though they are much larger than the Earth.
[src:light-probes/irradiance] This is a good approximation because the distance from even a nearby star to the Earth is much larger than the star's diameter.
[src:light-probes/irradiance] For instance, the irradiance of Alpha Centauri A (radiant flux: 1.5 L☉, distance: 4.34 ly) is about 2.7 × 10−8 W/m2 on Earth.
[src:light-probes/irradiance] The global irradiance on a horizontal surface on Earth consists of the direct irradiance *E*e,dir and diffuse irradiance *E*e,diff.
[src:light-probes/irradiance] On a tilted plane, there is another irradiance component, *E*e,refl, which is the component that is reflected from the ground.
[src:light-probes/irradiance] The average ground reflection is about 20% of the global irradiance.
[src:light-probes/irradiance] The integral of solar irradiance over a time period is called "solar exposure" or "insolation".
[src:light-probes/irradiance] Average solar irradiance at the top of the Earth's atmosphere is roughly 1361 W/m2, but at surface irradiance is approximately 1000 W/m2 on a clear day.
[src:light-probes/irradiance] Alternative symbols sometimes seen: W or E for radiant energy, P or F for radiant flux, I for irradiance, W for radiant exitance.
[src:light-probes/irradiance] Spectral quantities given per unit wavelength are denoted with suffix "*λ*".
[src:light-probes/irradiance] Directional quantities are denoted with suffix "Ω".
[src:light-probes/precomputed-radiance-transfer] In essence, PRT computes the illumination of a point as a linear combination of incident irradiance.
[src:light-probes/precomputed-radiance-transfer] An efficient method must be used to encode this data, such as spherical harmonics.
[src:light-probes/precomputed-radiance-transfer] When spherical harmonics are used to approximate the light transport function, only low-frequency effects can be handled with a reasonable number of parameters.
[src:light-probes/precomputed-radiance-transfer] Ren Ng et al. extended this work to handle higher frequency shadows by replacing spherical harmonics with non-linear wavelets.
[src:light-probes/precomputed-radiance-transfer] PRT is useful when an expensive light-transport simulation can be run offline and reused at run time.
[src:light-probes/precomputed-radiance-transfer] This allows effects such as soft shadows, interreflections and subsurface scattering to be included without changing the cost of the run-time shader for each added light in the environment.
[src:light-probes/precomputed-radiance-transfer] Standard PRT also has important restrictions: objects are usually assumed to be rigid, global effects are not preserved between independently moving objects, and low-order spherical harmonic lighting produces soft low-frequency shadows rather than sharp high-frequency detail.
[src:light-probes/precomputed-radiance-transfer] Local, deformable PRT extends the technique to deforming models by focusing on nearby surface details such as bumps and wrinkles, using zonal harmonics that can be rotated more cheaply than spherical harmonics.
[src:light-probes/precomputed-radiance-transfer] Sloan, Luna and Snyder demonstrated the method for real-time soft shadows, interreflections and subsurface scattering on deforming objects.
[src:light-probes/precomputed-radiance-transfer] PRT and related spherical-harmonic lighting have also appeared in game and graphics-library workflows.
[src:light-probes/precomputed-radiance-transfer] In *Halo 3*, Bungie described storing incoming lighting at surface points as spherical-harmonic vectors and using PRT lighting as part of the game's global-illumination pipeline.
[src:light-probes/precomputed-radiance-transfer] Direct3D 9's D3DX utility library included a PRT engine, compressed buffers and texture workflows for generating and representing transfer vectors.
[src:light-probes/precomputed-radiance-transfer] Teemu Mäki-Patola gives a clear introduction to the topic based on the work of Peter-Pike Sloan et al.
[src:light-probes/precomputed-radiance-transfer] At SIGGRAPH 2005, a detailed course on PRT was given.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonic-lighting] More intriguing techniques use SH to encode multiple functions—usually the global lighting environment and a per-vertex radiance transfer function.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonic-lighting] The generalized lighting equation involves, among other things, integrating the product of the incoming radiance and the BRDF over a sphere—something that is far too expensive for real-time rendering.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonic-lighting] But if the two functions are projected into SH coefficients, the integral of their product over the sphere is just the dot product of the two SH coefficient vectors.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonic-lighting] Generating the per-vertex transfer functions and projecting them to SH space is still an expensive process, but evaluating them is almost trivial.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonic-lighting] More to the point, they can be evaluated correctly even if the lighting environment changes in intensity or orientation.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonic-lighting] Even the most complex ray-traced radiosity algorithm can be rendered in real-time with dynamically changing lighting.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonic-lighting] SH lighting using preprocessed coefficients produces results that are beautiful but limited.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonic-lighting] Typically the lighting can change, or the lit mesh can be rotated, but the mesh can't be translated or deformed without requiring a new set of per-vertex coefficients.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonic-lighting] More recent techniques split the lighting equation into more parts and introduce techniques for updating SH components in real time or learn a transfer function which maps from shape deformations to updated per-vertex coefficients.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonic-lighting] Representing scene illumination using SH is increasingly popular in the field of neural rendering as the illumination in a scene can be predicted and manipulated using deep neural networks.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] In mathematics and physical science, **spherical harmonics** are special functions defined on the surface of a sphere.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] They are often employed in solving partial differential equations in many scientific fields.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] The table of spherical harmonics contains a list of common spherical harmonics.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] Since the spherical harmonics form a complete set of orthogonal functions and thus an orthonormal basis, certain functions defined on the surface of a sphere can be written as a sum of these spherical harmonics.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] This is similar to periodic functions defined on a circle that can be expressed as a sum of circular functions (sines and cosines) via Fourier series.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] Like the sines and cosines in Fourier series, the spherical harmonics may be organized by (spatial) angular frequency, as seen in the rows of functions in the illustration on the right.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] Further, spherical harmonics are basis functions for irreducible representations of SO(3), the group of rotations in three dimensions, and thus play a central role in the group theoretic discussion of SO(3).
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] Spherical harmonics originate from solving Laplace's equation in the spherical domains.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] Functions that are solutions to Laplace's equation are called harmonics.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] Despite their name, spherical harmonics take their simplest form in Cartesian coordinates, where they can be defined as homogeneous polynomials of degree $\ell$ in $(x,y,z)$ that obey Laplace's equation.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] In this setting, they may be viewed as the angular portion of a set of solutions to Laplace's equation in three dimensions, and this viewpoint is often taken as an alternative definition.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] Spherical harmonics, as functions on the sphere, are eigenfunctions of the Laplace-Beltrami operator (see Higher dimensions).
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] A specific set of spherical harmonics, denoted $Y_{\ell }^{m}(\theta ,\varphi )$ or $Y_{\ell }^{m}({\mathbf {r} })$ , are known as Laplace's spherical harmonics, as they were first introduced by Pierre Simon de Laplace in 1782.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] These functions form an orthogonal system, and are thus basic to the expansion of a general function on the sphere as alluded to above.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] In 3D computer graphics, spherical harmonics play a role in a wide variety of topics including indirect lighting (ambient occlusion, global illumination, precomputed radiance transfer, etc.) and modelling of 3D shapes.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] Spherical harmonics were first investigated in connection with the Newtonian potential of Newton's law of universal gravitation in three dimensions.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] Each term in the above summation is an individual Newtonian potential for a point mass.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] Just prior to that time, Adrien-Marie Legendre had investigated the expansion of the Newtonian potential in powers of *r* = |**x**| and *r*1 = |**x**1|.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] where *γ* is the angle between the vectors **x** and **x**1.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] The functions $P_{i}:[-1,1]\to \mathbb {R}$ are the Legendre polynomials, and they can be derived as a special case of spherical harmonics.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] Subsequently, in his 1782 memoir, Laplace investigated these coefficients using spherical coordinates to represent the angle *γ* between **x**1 and **x**.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] In 1867, William Thomson (Lord Kelvin) and Peter Guthrie Tait introduced the solid spherical harmonics in their *Treatise on Natural Philosophy*, and also first introduced the name of "spherical harmonics" for these functions.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] The 19th century development of Fourier series made possible the solution of a wide variety of physical problems in rectangular domains, such as the solution of the heat equation and wave equation.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] This could be achieved by expansion of functions in series of trigonometric functions.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] Whereas the trigonometric functions in a Fourier series represent the fundamental modes of vibration in a string, the spherical harmonics represent the fundamental modes of vibration of a sphere in much the same way.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] Many aspects of the theory of Fourier series could be generalized by taking expansions in spherical harmonics rather than trigonometric functions.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] Moreover, analogous to how trigonometric functions can equivalently be written as complex exponentials, spherical harmonics also possessed an equivalent form as complex-valued functions.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] This was a boon for problems possessing spherical symmetry, such as those of celestial mechanics originally studied by Laplace and Legendre.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] The prevalence of spherical harmonics already in physics set the stage for their later importance in the 20th century birth of quantum mechanics.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] The (complex-valued) spherical harmonics $S^{2}\to \mathbb {C}$ are eigenfunctions of the square of the orbital angular momentum operator $-i\hbar \mathbf {r} \times \nabla ,$ and therefore they represent the different quantized configurations of atomic orbitals.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] Laplace's equation imposes that the Laplacian of a scalar field *f* is zero.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] A priori, *m* is a complex constant, but because Φ must be a periodic function whose period evenly divides 2*π*, *m* is necessarily an integer and Φ is a linear combination of the complex exponentials *e*± *imφ*.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] The solution function *Y*(*θ*, *φ*) is regular at the poles of the sphere, where *θ* = 0, *π*.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] Furthermore, a change of variables *t* = cos *θ* transforms this equation into the Legendre equation, whose solution is a multiple of the associated Legendre polynomial *Pm ℓ*(cos *θ*) .
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] Finally, the equation for *R* has solutions of the form *R*(*r*) = *A rℓ* + *B r*−*ℓ* − 1; requiring the solution to be regular throughout **R**3 forces *B* = 0.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] Here the solution was assumed to have the special form *Y*(*θ*, *φ*) = Θ(*θ*) Φ(*φ*).
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] For a given value of *ℓ*, there are 2*ℓ* + 1 independent solutions of this form, one for each integer *m* with −*ℓ* ≤ *m* ≤ *ℓ*.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] Here $Y_{\ell }^{m}:S^{2}\to \mathbb {C}$ is called a **spherical harmonic function of degree *ℓ* and order *m***, $P_{\ell }^{m}:[-1,1]\to \mathbb {R}$ is an associated Legendre polynomial, *N* is a normalization constant, and *θ* and *φ* represent colatitude and longitude, respectively.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] In particular, the colatitude *θ*, or polar angle, ranges from *0* at the North Pole, to *π*/2 at the Equator, to *π* at the South Pole, and the longitude *φ*, or azimuth, may assume all values with 0 ≤ *φ* < 2*π*.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] In fact, for any such solution, *rℓ Y*(*θ*, *φ*) is the expression in spherical coordinates of a homogeneous polynomial $\mathbb {R} ^{3}\to \mathbb {C}$ that is harmonic (see below), and so counting dimensions shows that there are 2*ℓ* + 1 linearly independent such polynomials.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] where the $f_{\ell }^{m}\in \mathbb {C}$ are constants and the factors *rℓ Yℓm* are known as (*regular*) solid harmonics $\mathbb {R} ^{3}\to \mathbb {C}$ .
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] For $r>R$ , the solid harmonics with negative powers of r (the *irregular* solid harmonics $\mathbb {R} ^{3}\setminus \{\mathbf {0} \}\to \mathbb {C}$ ) are chosen instead.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] In that case, one needs to expand the solution of known regions in Laurent series (about $r=\infty$ ), instead of the Taylor series (about $r=0$ ) used above, to match the terms and find series expansion coefficients $f_{\ell }^{m}\in \mathbb {C}$ .
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] If *Y* is a joint eigenfunction of **L**2 and *L**z*, then by definition ${\begin{aligned}\mathbf {L} ^{2}Y&=\lambda Y\\L_{z}Y&=mY\end{aligned}}$ for some real numbers *m* and *λ*.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] Here *m* must in fact be an integer, for *Y* must be periodic in the coordinate *φ* with period a number that evenly divides 2*π*.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] In particular, *L**k* + : *E**λ*,*m* → *E**λ*,*m*+*k* must be zero for *k* sufficiently large, because the inequality *λ* ≥ *m*2 must hold in each of the nontrivial joint eigenspaces.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] The foregoing has been all worked out in the spherical coordinate representation, $\langle \theta ,\varphi |lm\rangle =Y_{l}^{m}(\theta ,\varphi )$ but may be expressed more abstractly in the complete, orthonormal spherical ket basis.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] The spherical harmonics can be expressed as the restriction to the unit sphere of certain polynomial functions $\mathbb {R} ^{3}\to \mathbb {C}$ .
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] Specifically, we say that a (complex-valued) polynomial function $p:\mathbb {R} ^{3}\to \mathbb {C}$ is *homogeneous* of degree $\ell$ if $p(\lambda \mathbf {x} )=\lambda ^{\ell }p(\mathbf {x} )$ for all real numbers $\lambda \in \mathbb {R}$ and all $\mathbf {x} \in \mathbb {R} ^{3}$ .
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] We say that p is *harmonic* if $\Delta p=0,$ where $\Delta$ is the Laplacian.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] For example, when $\ell =1$ , $\mathbf {A} _{1}$ is just the 3-dimensional space of all linear functions $\mathbb {R} ^{3}\to \mathbb {C}$ , since any such function is automatically harmonic.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] For any $\ell$ , the space $\mathbf {H} _{\ell }$ of spherical harmonics of degree $\ell$ is just the space of restrictions to the sphere $S^{2}$ of the elements of $\mathbf {A} _{\ell }$ .
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] As suggested in the introduction, this perspective is presumably the origin of the term "spherical harmonic" (i.e., the restriction to the sphere of a harmonic function).
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] For example, for any $c\in \mathbb {C}$ the formula $p(x_{1},x_{2},x_{3})=c(x_{1}+ix_{2})^{\ell }$ defines a homogeneous polynomial of degree $\ell$ with domain and codomain $\mathbb {R} ^{3}\to \mathbb {C}$ , which happens to be independent of $x_{3}$ .
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] This polynomial is easily seen to be harmonic.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] One source of confusion with the definition of the spherical harmonic functions concerns a phase factor of $(-1)^{m}$ , commonly referred to as the Condon–Shortley phase in the quantum mechanical literature.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] This phase factor may be included either in the definition of the associated Legendre polynomials or in the definition of the spherical harmonic functions, but it should not be counted twice.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] Some authors instead define associated Legendre functions without this phase factor.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] There is no requirement to use the Condon–Shortley phase in the definition of the spherical harmonic functions, but including it can simplify some quantum mechanical operations, especially the application of raising and lowering operators.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] The geodesy and magnetics communities commonly use conventions in which the Condon–Shortley phase factor is not included in the associated Legendre functions or in the spherical harmonics.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] Several different normalizations are in common use for the Laplace spherical harmonic functions $S^{2}\to \mathbb {C}$ .
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] These normalization choices are independent of the placement of the Condon–Shortley phase.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] The disciplines of geodesy and spectral analysis often use the corresponding $4\pi$ -normalized harmonics.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] The magnetics community, in contrast, often uses Schmidt semi-normalized harmonics.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] For the phase convention used in this article, the complex spherical harmonics satisfy $Y_{\ell }^{m}{}^{*}(\theta ,\varphi )=(-1)^{m}Y_{\ell }^{-m}(\theta ,\varphi ),$ where the superscript * denotes complex conjugation.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] This equation also follows from the relation of the spherical harmonic functions with the Wigner D-matrix.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] The real spherical harmonics $Y_{\ell m}:S^{2}\to \mathbb {R}$ are sometimes known as *tesseral spherical harmonics*.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] These functions have the same orthonormality properties as the complex ones $Y_{\ell }^{m}:S^{2}\to \mathbb {C}$ above.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] The real spherical harmonics $Y_{\ell m}$ with *m* > 0 are said to be of cosine type, and those with *m* < 0 of sine type.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] With a different placement of that phase, the displayed signs must be changed consistently.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] The same sine and cosine factors can be also seen in the following subsection that deals with the Cartesian representation.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] See here for a list of real spherical harmonics up to and including $\ell =4$ , which can be seen to be consistent with the output of the equations above.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] From the analytic solutions for the hydrogen atom, the eigenfunctions of the angular part of the wave function are spherical harmonics.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] However, the solutions of the non-relativistic Schrödinger equation without magnetic terms can be made real.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] This is why the real forms are extensively used in basis functions for quantum chemistry, as the programs do not then need to use complex algebra.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] Here, the real functions span the same space as the complex ones would.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] For example, as can be seen from the table of spherical harmonics, the usual *p* functions ( $\ell =1$ ) are complex and mix axis directions, but the real versions are essentially just *x*, *y*, and *z*.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] More specifically, it is the (unique up to normalization) Gelfand-Tsetlin-basis of this representation of the rotational group $SO(3)$ and an explicit formula for $R_{\ell }^{m}$ in cartesian coordinates can be derived from that fact.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] It suffices to take v and $\lambda$ as real parameters.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] In naming this generating function after Herglotz, we follow Courant & Hilbert 1962, §VII.7, who credit unpublished notes by him for its discovery.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] Essentially all the properties of the spherical harmonics can be derived from this generating function.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] They are, moreover, a standardized set with a fixed scale or normalization.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] The factor ${\bar {\Pi }}_{\ell }^{m}(z)$ is essentially the associated Legendre polynomial $P_{\ell }^{m}(\cos \theta )$ , and the factors $(A_{m}\pm iB_{m})$ are essentially $e^{\pm im\varphi }$ .
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] The spherical harmonics have deep and consequential properties under the operations of spatial inversion (parity) and rotation.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] The spherical harmonics have definite parity.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] That is, they are either even or odd with respect to inversion about the origin.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] Inversion is represented by the operator $P\Psi (\mathbf {r} )=\Psi (-\mathbf {r} )$ .
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] In terms of the spherical angles, parity transforms a point with coordinates $\{\theta ,\varphi \}$ to $\{\pi -\theta ,\pi +\varphi \}$ .
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] Parity continues to hold for real spherical harmonics, and for spherical harmonics in higher dimensions: applying a point reflection to a spherical harmonic of degree ℓ changes the sign by a factor of (−1)*ℓ*.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] Consider a rotation ${\mathcal {R}}$ about the origin that sends the unit vector $\mathbf {r}$ to $\mathbf {r} '$ .
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] Under this operation, a spherical harmonic of degree $\ell$ and order m transforms into a linear combination of spherical harmonics of the same degree.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] However, this is not the standard way of expressing this property.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] The rotational behavior of the spherical harmonics is perhaps their quintessential feature from the viewpoint of group theory.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] The $Y_{\ell }^{m}$ 's of degree $\ell$ provide a basis set of functions for the irreducible representation of the group SO(3) of dimension $(2\ell +1)$ .
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] Many facts about spherical harmonics (such as the addition theorem) that are proved laboriously using the methods of analysis acquire simpler proofs and deeper significance using the methods of symmetry.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] The Laplace spherical harmonics $Y_{\ell }^{m}:S^{2}\to \mathbb {C}$ form a complete set of orthonormal functions and thus form an orthonormal basis of the Hilbert space of square-integrable functions $L_{\mathbb {C} }^{2}(S^{2})$ .
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] The expansion coefficients are the analogs of Fourier coefficients, and can be obtained by multiplying the above equation by the complex conjugate of a spherical harmonic, integrating over the solid angle Ω, and utilizing the above orthogonality relationships.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] This is justified rigorously by basic Hilbert space theory.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] If the coefficients decay in *ℓ* sufficiently rapidly — for instance, exponentially — then the series also converges uniformly to *f*.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] The convergence of the series holds again in the same sense, namely the real spherical harmonics $Y_{\ell m}:S^{2}\to \mathbb {R}$ form a complete set of orthonormal functions and thus form an orthonormal basis of the Hilbert space of square-integrable functions $L_{\mathbb {R} }^{2}(S^{2})$ .
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] The completeness relation is a distributional equality between a sum over all indices and the Dirac delta function.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] For the spherical harmonics, the Dirac delta is the tensor product of two Dirac delta functions, one for the azimuthal angle on the sphere, and one for the polar angle.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] The total power of a function *f* is defined in the signal processing literature as the integral of the function squared, divided by the area of its domain.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] is defined as the angular power spectrum (for Schmidt semi-normalized harmonics).
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] If the functions *f* and *g* have a zero mean (i.e., the spectral coefficients *f*00 and *g*00 are zero), then *S**ff*(*ℓ*) and *S**fg*(*ℓ*) represent the contributions to the function's variance and covariance for degree ℓ, respectively.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] When *β* = 0, the spectrum is "white" as each degree possesses equal power.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] When *β* < 0, the spectrum is termed "red" as there is more power at the low degrees with long wavelengths than higher degrees.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] Finally, when *β* > 0, the spectrum is termed "blue".
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] The condition on the order of growth of *S**ff*(*ℓ*) is related to the order of differentiability of *f* in the next section.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] Spherical harmonics are used to approximate functions on the sphere, and the order of decay of the power governs smoothness.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] Let $\Pi _{n}(S^{2})$ denote the space spanned by spherical harmonics of degree at most n .
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] with the norm taken in $L^{p}(S^{2})$ , or in the uniform norm when $p=\infty$ .
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] The asymptotic behavior of $E_{n}(f)_{p}$ as $n\to \infty$ gives a quantitative measure of how well f can be approximated by low-degree spherical harmonics.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] This is analogous to approximation by trigonometric polynomials in ordinary Fourier analysis.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] On the circle, smoothness can be measured by the decay of Fourier coefficients.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] On the sphere, smoother functions admit faster approximation by spherical polynomials, while conversely, sufficiently rapid decay of the approximation error implies smoothness.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] More precisely, Sobolev-type smoothness can also be described spectrally, since spherical harmonics of degree $\ell$ are eigenfunctions of the Laplace–Beltrami operator with eigenvalue $-\ell (\ell +1)$ .
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] For $p=2$ this relation can be stated especially explicitly.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] Thus $f\in H^{s}(S^{2})$ precisely when this weighted sum is finite.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] Since $\ell (\ell +1)$ grows like $\ell ^{2}$ , higher Sobolev smoothness requires faster decay of the power in high degrees.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] which bounds the approximation error by the Sobolev norm.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] With the above power normalization, a decay estimate of the form $S_{ff}(\ell )=O(\ell ^{-\alpha })$ implies membership in $H^{s}(S^{2})$ whenever $\alpha >2s+1$ .
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p01] Thus sufficiently fast polynomial decay of the power spectrum implies differentiability, and decay faster than every power implies smoothness of all orders.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p02] A mathematical result of considerable interest and use is called the *addition theorem* for spherical harmonics.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p02] where *P**ℓ* is the Legendre polynomial of degree ℓ.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p02] This expression is valid for both real and complex harmonics.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p02] The result can be proven analytically, using the properties of the Poisson kernel in the unit ball, or geometrically by applying a rotation to the vector **y** so that it points along the *z*-axis, and then directly calculating the right-hand side.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p02] In the expansion (**1**), the left-hand side $P_{\ell }(\mathbf {x} \cdot \mathbf {y} )$ is a constant multiple of the degree ℓ zonal spherical harmonic.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p02] From this perspective, one has the following generalization to higher dimensions.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p02] Let *Y**j* be an arbitrary orthonormal basis of the space **H***ℓ* of degree ℓ spherical harmonics on the n-sphere.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p02] Combining (**2**) and (**3**) gives (**1**) in dimension *n* = 2 when **x** and **y** are represented in spherical coordinates.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p02] The values of c and $\gamma$ that result in non-zero terms in this sum are determined by the selection rules for the 3j-symbols.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p02] The Clebsch–Gordan coefficients are the coefficients appearing in the expansion of the product of two spherical harmonics in terms of spherical harmonics themselves.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p02] A variety of techniques are available for doing essentially the same calculation, including the Wigner 3-jm symbol, the Racah coefficients, and the Slater integrals.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p02] Abstractly, the Clebsch–Gordan coefficients express the tensor product of two irreducible representations of the rotation group as a sum of irreducible representations: suitably normalized, the coefficients are then the multiplicities.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p02] The Laplace spherical harmonics $Y_{\ell }^{m}$ can be visualized by considering their "nodal lines", that is, the set of points on the sphere where $\Re [Y_{\ell }^{m}]=0$ , or alternatively where $\Im [Y_{\ell }^{m}]=0$ .
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p02] Nodal lines of $Y_{\ell }^{m}$ are composed of *ℓ* circles: there are |*m*| circles along longitudes and *ℓ*−|*m*| circles along latitudes.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p02] One can determine the number of nodal lines of each type by counting the number of zeros of $Y_{\ell }^{m}$ in the $\theta$ and $\varphi$ directions respectively.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p02] Considering $Y_{\ell }^{m}$ as a function of $\theta$ , the real and imaginary components of the associated Legendre polynomials each possess *ℓ*−|*m*| zeros, each giving rise to a nodal 'line of latitude'.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p02] On the other hand, considering $Y_{\ell }^{m}$ as a function of $\varphi$ , the trigonometric sin and cos functions possess 2|*m*| zeros, each of which gives rise to a nodal 'line of longitude'.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p02] When the spherical harmonic order *m* is zero (upper-left in the figure), the spherical harmonic functions do not depend upon longitude, and are referred to as ***zonal***.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p02] Such spherical harmonics are a special case of zonal spherical functions.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p02] When *ℓ* = |*m*| (bottom-right in the figure), there are no zero crossings in latitude, and the functions are referred to as ***sectoral***.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p02] For the other cases, the functions checker the sphere, and they are referred to as ***tesseral***.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p02] More general spherical harmonics of degree ℓ are not necessarily those of the Laplace basis $Y_{\ell }^{m}$ , and their nodal sets can be of a fairly general kind.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p02] The classical spherical harmonics are defined as complex-valued functions on the unit sphere $S^{2}$ inside three-dimensional Euclidean space $\mathbb {R} ^{3}$ .
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p02] Spherical harmonics can be generalized to higher-dimensional Euclidean space $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ as follows, leading to functions $S^{n-1}\to \mathbb {C}$ .
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p02] Let **P***ℓ* denote the space of complex-valued homogeneous polynomials of degree ℓ in n real variables, here considered as functions $\mathbb {R} ^{n}\to \mathbb {C}$ .
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p02] Let **A***ℓ* denote the subspace of **P***ℓ* consisting of all harmonic polynomials: $\mathbf {A} _{\ell }:=\{p\in \mathbf {P} _{\ell }\,\mid \,\Delta p=0\}\,.$ These are the (regular) solid spherical harmonics.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p02] The space **H***ℓ* of spherical harmonics of degree ℓ is a representation of the symmetry group of rotations around a point (SO(3)) and its double-cover SU(2).
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p02] Indeed, rotations act on the two-dimensional sphere, and thus also on **H***ℓ* by function composition $\psi \mapsto \psi \circ \rho ^{-1}$ for ψ a spherical harmonic and ρ a rotation.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p02] The representation **H***ℓ* is an irreducible representation of SO(3).
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p02] The elements of **H***ℓ* arise as the restrictions to the sphere of elements of **A***ℓ*: harmonic polynomials homogeneous of degree ℓ on three-dimensional Euclidean space **R**3.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p02] Thus as an irreducible representation of SO(3), **H***ℓ* is isomorphic to the space of traceless symmetric tensors of degree ℓ.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p02] More generally, the analogous statements hold in higher dimensions: the space **H***ℓ* of spherical harmonics on the n-sphere is the irreducible representation of SO(*n*+1) corresponding to the traceless symmetric ℓ-tensors.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p02] However, whereas every irreducible tensor representation of SO(2) and SO(3) is of this kind, the special orthogonal groups in higher dimensions have additional irreducible representations that do not arise in this manner.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p02] The special orthogonal groups have additional spin representations that are not tensor representations, and are *typically* not spherical harmonics.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p02] An exception are the spin representation of SO(3): strictly speaking these are representations of the double cover SU(2) of SO(3).
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p02] In turn, SU(2) is identified with the group of unit quaternions, and so coincides with the 3-sphere.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p02] The spaces of spherical harmonics on the 3-sphere are certain spin representations of SO(3), with respect to the action by quaternionic multiplication.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p02] Spherical harmonics can be separated into two sets of functions.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p02] One is hemispherical harmonics (HSH), orthogonal and complete on hemisphere.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p02] Another is complementary hemispherical harmonics (CHSH).
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p02] The angle-preserving symmetries of the two-sphere are described by the group of Möbius transformations PSL(2,**C**).
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p02] With respect to this group, the sphere is equivalent to the usual Riemann sphere.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p02] The group PSL(2,**C**) is isomorphic to the (proper) Lorentz group, and its action on the two-sphere agrees with the action of the Lorentz group on the celestial sphere in Minkowski space.
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p02] The analog of the spherical harmonics for the Lorentz group is given by the hypergeometric series; furthermore, the spherical harmonics can be re-expressed in terms of the hypergeometric series, as SO(3) = PSU(2) is a subgroup of PSL(2,**C**).
[src:light-probes/spherical-harmonics-p02] More generally, hypergeometric series can be generalized to describe the symmetries of any symmetric space; in particular, hypergeometric series can be developed for any Lie group.
